“Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, and this is particularly true in men up to sixty-six,” said the study’s co-author, Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University in Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health concerns, Mrs. Eeles added.
During 1994-2009 she and her colleagues in Britain pursued more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants of the study, the point finger was shorter on the right hand than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and display fingers were the same long.
However, in men whose show finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, already in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones that the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer display finger.
