The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves before their consultation with the Consulate at the Service Offices for visa application; costs will be reduced in this way.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the Embassy of the United States and the Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves before their conversation in the Consulate at the Visa Application Services (ASC, the initial letters in English).
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant being reviewed by the consulate before the conversation.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of handling the visa is reduced because it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out.
The applicant only makes a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the contradiction to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for time workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa need not speak in the consulate, they only have to imagine themselves at the nearest ASC, where they submit their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric data are collected in the ASC, the applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those applying for the visa in the Consulates of Ciudad Thuringia, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the service charge of $26.
Additional information about the new visa application procedure can be found in the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
